{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17473189","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17473189"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:05:27+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:05:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2019"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2019","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2019"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.62,0.12,0.14,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2019"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54546"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2019","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2019"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2019"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40055"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"1021"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4971"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11632"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"666"},{"type":"contributions","id":"876"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9893"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9901"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16734"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42432"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44064"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54546","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/54546"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 16-year-old girl presents to the General Practice clinic with a several-month history of fatigue and low energy. She reports feeling more susceptible to the cold recently. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She reached menarche at age 12 and previously had a regular 28-day menstrual cycle with 3-4 days of bleeding. However, over the last six months, she has only had two scanty periods. On diet history, she reports limiting her intake due to concern about weight gain and keeps track of calories consumed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 55/min, blood pressure 100/65 mmHg, respiratory rate 14/min, SpO2 99% on room air, and temperature 36.2\u00b0C. She has a slim build with a BMI of 16.5 kg/m2. There is no pallor. Secondary sexual characteristics are evident. She has mild facial acne. There is no hirsutism or cushingoid features. She does not have any tremor, and examination of her neck is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following hormones is most likely to be reduced in this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cortisol","T3","Growth hormone","Adrenocorticotropic hormone (ACTH)","Arginine vasopressin (ADH)"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s presentation is consistent with anorexia nervosa, characterized by restricted food intake, low BMI, and amenorrhoea. The endocrine changes in anorexia nervosa are complex and involve multiple hormonal axes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ET3\u003C/strong\u003E levels are typically decreased in individuals with anorexia nervosa. This is likely an adaptive response to reduce metabolic rate and resting energy expenditure. It is a form of nonthyroidal illness syndrome, where TSH and T4 levels may remain normal or decrease. This adaptive response usually does not require treatment, as thyroid hormone supplementation could potentially exacerbate weight loss and be subject to abuse.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECortisol\u003C/strong\u003E levels are generally elevated in anorexia nervosa. This is due to increased corticotropin-releasing hormone (CRH) production in response to the stress of chronic nutritional deprivation. Elevated cortisol helps maintain euglycaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGrowth hormone\u003C/strong\u003E levels typically rise in anorexia nervosa due to resistance at the liver secondary to chronic nutritional deprivation. This increase may serve a protective function by maintaining euglycaemia through gluconeogenesis and mobilising fat stores via lipolysis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EACTH\u003C/strong\u003E production is usually increased in anorexia nervosa, paralleling the rise in CRH and cortisol. This is part of the overall stress response to chronic nutritional deprivation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EADH\u003C/strong\u003E (also known as vasopressin) levels are typically elevated in anorexia nervosa. This can occasionally lead to hyponatraemia, a condition known as the syndrome of inappropriate antidiuretic hormone secretion (SIADH).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s worth noting that while not mentioned in the options, oestradiol levels are also typically reduced in anorexia nervosa. This is due to reduced gonadotropin-releasing hormone (GnRH) secretion from the hypothalamus, resulting in reduced pulsatility of luteinising hormone (LH). This leads to the hypothalamic amenorrhoea seen in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Anorexia nervosa typically results in decreased T3 and oestradiol levels, but causes elevated GH, cortisol, ACTH, and ADH levels.","Nonthyroidal illness syndrome in anorexia nervosa is an adaptive response and does not typically require treatment.","Hypothalamic amenorrhoea in anorexia nervosa is due to reduced GnRH secretion and LH pulsatility."],"references":["Schorr M, Miller KK. The endocrine manifestations of anorexia nervosa: mechanisms and management. Nature Reviews Endocrinology. 2017 Mar;13(3):174-86. https://www.nature.com/articles/nrendo.2016.175","Misra M, Klibanski A. Endocrine consequences of anorexia nervosa. The lancet Diabetes \u0026 endocrinology. 2014 Jul 1;2(7):581-92. https://www.thelancet.com/journals/landia/article/PIIS2213-8587(13)70180-3/fulltext"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40055"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2019"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40055","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/40055"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-07T11:02:13+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-07T11:04:02+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2019"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54546"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":